<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-02-23T17:45:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-02-23T17:45:00-05:00" n="522" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d522">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00/7942: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Lane</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-02-23T17:00:00-05:45">February 23, 1934—5
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 6:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>62. There have been no disorders in Managua following death of Sandino,
                            although situation is still somewhat tense with state of siege in force
                            and telegraph and telephone communications restricted. <pb facs="0600" n="534" xml:id="pg_534"/> Granada is quiet according to a reliable
                            report, and American Consul at Puerto Cabezas reports everything quiet
                            in that region.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to Central American Missions.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Lane</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>